            <para>
                Normally, if you don't have a skill then you can't use it. Some skills
                <e>default</e> to another skill. In this case, you can use the default skill
                instead, however the result you roll is halved. Many physical skills will
                default to either an <e>Attribute</e> or a <e>Talent</e>.
            </para>
            
            <sect2>
                <title>Techniques</title>
                
                <para>
                    Many skills have <e>Techniques</e> associated with them. When your skill
                    reaches a level equal to the cost of the <e>Technique</e> then you can
                    purchase it with <e>Experience</e>. <e>Techniques</e> often allow you to do
                    things which would wouldn't normally be able to do, or make some things
                    easier. There are various different types of technique.
                </para>
                
                <sect3>
                    <title>Specialisations</title>
                    
                    <para>
                        A <e>Skill Specialisation</e> is a type of <e>Technique</e> that allows
                        you to learn some narrow use of the skill. For example, the <e>Survival</e>
                        skill has specialisations in different types of terrain and climate.
                        If you don't have a relevant specialisation, then you default to the skill
                        itself, which means that your roll is halved.
                    </para>
                    <para>
                        Specialisations can be either <e>Easy</e> or <e>Hard</e>. An <e>Easy</e>
                        specialisation costs 2 points, and a <e>Hard</e> specialisation costs 4
                        points.
                    </para>
                </sect3>
                
                <sect3>
                    <title>Skill Mastery</title>
                    
                    <para>
                        A <e>Skill Mastery</e> is like a specialisation but more flexible. They
                        are generally used when the most common usage of a skill is in an opposed
                        roll against another person with the skill. In a quick contest, the
                        opponent with the highest <e>Mastery</e> level can either re-roll their
                        roll, or force a re-roll of their opponents. In a long contest, then they
                        get a number of re-rolls equal to the difference in mastery levels.
                    </para>
                    
                    <para>
                        Alternatively, a <e>Skill Mastery</e> may be used for open ended craft or
                        performance skills.
                    </para>
                </sect3>
            </sect2>

